The Stage of May
London — — Stands before the newly appointed British Prime Minister Theresa May a daunting task: to implement the "exit from the European Union" requirement of British people — — or more specifically, the English and Welsh — — voters and manage the far-reaching consequences of this work.
This challenge she faces is dwarfed by her predecessors in recent years.
But she may be able to complete this task.
No one should underestimate May.
Just like German Chancellor Merkel, who has shown courage in a series of crises, Angela Merkel has all the tools needed to complete the task at her disposal.
She is smart, tenacious, and has no patience for nonsense.
She has a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not bound by any ideology, is very skilled at gaining control, and operates within the boundaries she has set herself to ensure familiarity with the issues at hand.
Angela Merkel has won most of the battles she has participated in, and shows no mercy to those who have used underhanded methods to deal with her.
But she has few enemies within the party and is quite popular among ordinary party members.
This is a powerful combination – she needs to make the most of it to lead the UK's Brexit process.
The UK's Brexit process has already begun, and there's no doubt about it.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland vote to stay in the EU, May has repeatedly stated that the Brexit referendum cannot be reversed.
She has repeatedly stated “Brexit means Brexit,” and her ministers all agree with her view.
But May has not given an exact definition of Brexit.
This task is very difficult to complete.
Imagine someone saying to you, "Breakfast is breakfast," and then starts preparing your food.
You will find it hard to know clearly what you will actually eat.
A Northern Irish "Ulster fry" – scrambled eggs, bacon, sausage, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread, and fried tomatoes – with a cup of tea?
Coffee and pastries?
Depending on your environment and personal preferences, you might feel very differently about various possible combinations.
The same situation also applies to Brexit.
Some people might be mainly concerned with blocking EU labor from entering the UK.
Others might be more concerned with securing single market access rights.
But different from breakfast is that the UK cannot order every dish on the menu, each one a portion.
The reality often ignored by the Leave camp is that the EU will not give the UK all the benefits for free.
This is not because the EU leaders want to win people's hearts or punish the UK for refusing the EU (such inflammatory rhetoric is often heard, such as Boris Johnson's recent statement about "Hitler-style imperialism").
Rather, we Britons often forget that everyone – including the EU and all its member states – has their own political or commercial interests to protect.
For May, the core challenge in the coming months will be to determine, on a realistic basis, what the UK's goals should be after the start of the tough negotiations on its relations with the EU (which also involve its relations with the rest of the world).
Considering the scope involved in the agenda (I can think of at least six major topics that need separate negotiations), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
(When the negotiation is completed, my 11-year-old granddaughter may have already started college!)
) We must clearly define our priorities to prevent the negotiation from taking even longer.
The goal, of course, is to balance the entry of British goods and services (especially financial services) into other European countries and restrict the entry of EU citizens into the UK.
The more concessions negotiators get in one area, the greater the concessions they must make in other areas.
Mei needs to fully utilize the knowledge, skills, and political capital she possesses to ensure the rationality of the negotiation transaction.
However, even if she succeeds in achieving her goals, she will still find that not everyone is satisfied - such a result is inevitable - and it is everyone.
This will exacerbate another major challenge faced by the Mei government: narrowing the increasingly large gaps in British society exposed by the UK's exit from the EU.
The blue-collar workers in northern and central England are the main force behind the UK's Brexit referendum, having always been distant from political leaders, left behind by globalization, and marginalized by the so-called agent - the EU - of globalization.
England's major cities - especially London - may have benefited greatly from globalization, but they have not received any benefits.
Due to the lack of confidence in Jeremy Corbyn-led Labour Party, members of the working-class community ultimately became prey to the Brexit populist's promises.
"We will reverse globalization," they claim.
"We will chase away low-wage immigrants and transfer the hundreds of millions of pounds originally given to the EU to public services."
They promise that Brexit will bring back a more secure and prosperous past for Britain.
Brexit advocates cannot truly fulfill these promises.
Globalization cannot be reversed, nor can the flow of immigrants from the EU be cut off.
Any such measure will only destroy British businesses.
Even if the economy is not good, resulting in a decrease in immigration, the workers who voted for Brexit may still find low-paying jobs to be low-paying, and the pressure on public services remains heavy.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has unleashed an uncontrollable wave of populist sentiment.
Just like Donald Trump was unable to improve the circumstances of American working-class voters, Brexit is also unable to bring any benefits to those who chose it, regardless of how the situation may seem.
Although it has many advantages, such a challenge may still be insurmountable for Starmer.
